reproduce racial and neocolonial dispossession. From the archives of Christian fair traders to luxury social entrepreneurship conferences, from US finance offices to Guatemalan towns flooded with their loan products, from service economy desperation to the internal contradictions of social movements, Hulsether argues that capitalist humanitarian projects are fueled as much by a profit motive as by a hope that racial capitalism can redeem the losses that accumulate in its wake.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCapitalismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aCapitalismxReligious aspects. 0aEconomic assistancexMoral and ethical aspectszDeveloping countries. 0aHumanitarianismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aNeoliberalismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023 Englishz978311131928508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023z9783111318820oZDB-23-DGF40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023838?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023838423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023838/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131928-5  EBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_E